Notes

- Most of today’s evidence is code/doc/test-level, not live runtime proof.
- The supported-profile alignment and current-state updates strengthen release truth, but they do not expand the supported surface.
- The heartbeat work is materially more bounded now, but publication safety still depends on the review and outbox flow being followed, not just present in the repo.
- The runtime boundary work is conservative by design: deny-first transport and symlink-aware writes reduce risk rather than adding new capability.

Next likely moves

- Run the new Flow Builder contracts through focused tests and fix any mismatches between the persistence model and runtime behavior.
- Exercise the heartbeat review/staging/outbox path end to end and look for gaps between script-level success and actual publication truth.
- Keep the supported-profile proof current if runtime wiring drifts again.
- Expand contract coverage around any adjacent surfaces that still infer state indirectly.
- Separate any remaining claim-generation work from runtime-proof work so evidence stays honest.

Closing thought

The main shift today was not feature count. It was truth density. More of Codexify’s important surfaces now carry explicit contracts, stricter gates, and better failure language, which makes the system easier to trust without pretending it is finished.



